nesses. Water cures were endorsed by both orthodox and unorthodox practitioners and attracted growing numbers of patients into the twentieth century. It examines how institutions and skilled workers shaped the development of specialist resorts and considers why the NHS support for spa treatment declined from the 1960s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHealth resortszEnglandxHistory. 0aMineral watersxTherapeutic use. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  acures.  ahealing.  ahydropathy.  aleisure.  aregimen.  aresort.  aspa.  aunorthodox.  awater.1 aAdams, Jane M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978071909807940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780719098079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780719098079/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles